The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 Thursday, April 14, 2005 

 BRIEFS

 Calcutta, April 13: The CPM leadership today rallied behind Biman Bose, who had yesterday declared he would raise funds from people to contest in the Supreme Court a Calcutta High Court verdict sentencing him to three days? imprisonment and slapping a fine of Rs 10,000 for making derogatory remarks about the judiciary. 

 ?All our party members will donate Re 1 each to contest the judgment in the apex court,? said CPM state secretary Anil Biswas. 

 Calcutta: The mother of a 12-year-old girl, missing since January 2003, has moved Calcutta High Court, seeking a directive to police to bring her daughter back, dead or alive. Basanti Roy, a resident of Habra in North 24-Parganas, alleged that neither the police nor the chief minister?s office had taken any steps to trace Kanan.

 Calcutta: The government has transferred 18 IPS and lower level police officers. Rakesh Kumar Gupta and L. Lengkhottan Downgel ? both on deputation at the Centre ? have been posted as DIG (enforcement branch) and DIG (armed police), Siliguri.

 Chinsurah: A 17-year-old higher secondary candidate committed suicide by hanging herself with her dupatta at her home in Mankundu, about 25 km from Calcutta. Family members have told the police that Barnali Hazra was suffering from depression.

 Calcutta: Residents of Chitpur demonstrated in front of NRS Medical College and Hospital on Wednesday night after the death of 32-year-old Birendra Jadav, allegedly because of negligence by attending doctors.




